1. History & Key Features
Java was created by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems in 1995. It was originally designed for interactive television but was too advanced for the digital cable industry at the time.
Key Features (The "Buzzwords")
●	Platform Independent: "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA).
●	Object-Oriented (OOP): Everything is an object, which makes the code modular and reusable.
●	Robust: Strong memory management and lack of pointers (which prevents many security issues).
●	Multithreaded: Java can perform multiple tasks simultaneously, which is vital for modern web applications.
________________________________________
2. JVM vs. JRE vs. JDK
These three are the heart of the Java platform. Think of them as layers of a nesting doll.
●	JVM (Java Virtual Machine): The "engine." It’s an abstract machine that provides the runtime environment where Java bytecode is executed. It is platform-dependent (different for Windows vs. Linux).
●	JRE (Java Runtime Environment): The "package." It contains the JVM + libraries + other files that allow a Java program to run. If you only want to play a Java-based game, you only need the JRE.
●	JDK (Java Development Kit): The "toolbox." It contains the JRE + development tools (like the compiler javac and debugger). As a developer, this is what you install.
________________________________________
3. Compilation & Execution Flow
In many languages, you compile code directly into machine code (binary). Java uses a two-step process to ensure it can run on any device.
1.	Compilation: You write code in a .java file. You run javac MyFile.java. The compiler checks for syntax errors and converts the code into Bytecode (.class file).
2.	Execution: You run java MyFile. The JVM takes the bytecode and converts it into machine-specific code that your computer's processor understands.
________________________________________
4. The Bytecode Concept
Bytecode is the magic middleman. It is a highly optimized set of instructions that isn't specific to any one processor.
Because the compiler produces Bytecode rather than Machine Code, you can take a .class file generated on Windows and run it on a Mac without changing a single line of code—provided the Mac has a JVM installed.
________________________________________
5. Java Program Structure
A standard Java file follows a specific hierarchy:
1.	Documentation/Package: Optional, but used to organize classes.
2.	Import Statements: To bring in external libraries (e.g., import java.util.Scanner;).
3.	Class Declaration: Every line of code in Java must be inside a class.
4.	Methods & Variables: The logic and data.
Java
package com.myproject; // Package

import java.util.ArrayList; // Import

public class Main { // Class
    public static void main(String[] args) { // Main Method
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
