7. Command Line Arguments
Command line arguments are parameters passed to the program during execution. They are stored in the String[] args array.
Example: If you run your program like this: java MyProgram Hello 123
Inside your code:
●	args[0] would be "Hello"
●	args[1] would be "123"
This is incredibly useful for passing configuration settings or file paths to your backend without hardcoding them.
1. Variables & Data Types
In Java, a variable is a container that holds data. Because Java is statically typed, you must declare the type of data a variable will hold before you can use it.
Java
int studentId = 101; // 'int' is the type, 'studentId' is the name
________________________________________
2. Primitive Data Types
Primitive types are the most basic data types predefined by the language. They are not objects and hold their values directly in memory.
Category	Type	Size	Range / Description
Integer	byte	1 byte	-128 to 127
	short	2 bytes	-32,768 to 32,767
	int	4 bytes	~-2 billion to 2 billion (Standard choice)
	long	8 bytes	Very large numbers (Suffix with 'L', e.g., 10L)
Floating Point	float	4 bytes	6-7 decimal digits (Suffix with 'f')
	double	8 bytes	15 decimal digits (Standard for decimals)
Character	char	2 bytes	A single Unicode character (e.g., 'A')
Logical	boolean	1 bit	true or false
________________________________________
3. Non-Primitive (Reference) Types
Non-primitive types refer to objects. They are created by the programmer (except for String, which is built-in but still a reference type).
●	Strings: Sequence of characters. String name = "Java";
●	Arrays: Collections of similar data types. int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3};
●	Classes/Interfaces: Custom types you define.
Key Difference: Primitives always have a value (e.g., int defaults to 0), whereas Non-primitives can be null.
________________________________________
4. Type Casting
Type casting is when you assign a value of one primitive data type to another type.
Widening Casting (Automatic)
Converting a smaller type to a larger type size. There is no data loss.
byte -> short -> char -> int -> long -> float -> double
Java
int myInt = 9;
double myDouble = myInt; // Automatic casting: 9.0
Narrowing Casting (Manual)
Converting a larger type to a smaller size. You must do this manually because data loss can occur.
Java
double myDouble = 9.78;
int myInt = (int) myDouble; // Manual casting: 9 (decimal is lost)
________________________________________
5. Wrapper Classes
For every primitive type, Java provides a corresponding Wrapper Class. This "wraps" the primitive in an object.
Primitive	Wrapper Class
int	Integer
char	Character
double	Double
boolean	Boolean
Why use them?
1.	Collections: You cannot store primitives in a List. You must use ArrayList<Integer>, not ArrayList<int>.
2.	Utility Methods: They provide methods like Integer.parseInt("123") to convert strings to numbers.
3.	Autoboxing/Unboxing: Java automatically converts between primitives and wrappers.
________________________________________
6. Constants (final keyword)
In Java, if you want a variable's value to stay unchangeable (read-only), you use the final keyword.
Java
final double PI = 3.14159;
// PI = 3.14; // This would cause a compile-time error

