1. Decision Making: if / else
The if statement is the most basic control flow. It executes a block of code only if a specific condition is true.
Java
int userAge = 20;

if (userAge >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Access Granted");
} else if (userAge > 13) {
    System.out.println("Limited Access");
} else {
    System.out.println("Access Denied");
}
●	Key Rule: The condition inside the () must result in a boolean. Unlike JavaScript, Java won't treat an integer 1 as true.
________________________________________
2. Selection: switch
When you have multiple discrete values to check (like a menu or a status code), switch is much cleaner than multiple if-else blocks.
Java
String orderStatus = "SHIPPED";

switch (orderStatus) {
    case "PENDING":
        System.out.println("Order is being prepared.");
        break;
    case "SHIPPED":
        System.out.println("Order is on the way.");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Status unknown.");
}
●	The break keyword: Very important! If you forget it, Java will "fall through" and execute the next case regardless of the value.
________________________________________
3. The for Loop
Used when you know exactly how many times you want to repeat a task (e.g., iterating through an array of items to send to the frontend).
Java
// Initialization; Condition; Increment
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println("Iteration: " + i);
}
●	Enhanced For Loop: Often used for collections.
for (String item : itemList) { ... }
________________________________________
4. while Loop
Repeats a block of code as long as a condition remains true. Use this when you don't know the exact number of iterations in advance.
Java
int count = 0;
while (count < 3) {
    System.out.println("Count is: " + count);
    count++;
}
________________________________________
5. do-while Loop
Similar to while, but it guarantees that the code block will execute at least once before the condition is checked.
Java
int i = 10;
do {
    System.out.println("This will print once even though 10 < 5 is false");
} while (i < 5);
________________________________________
6. Branching: break and continue
These keywords give you fine-grained control inside loops.
●	break: Completely exits the loop immediately.
●	continue: Skips the current iteration and jumps to the next one.
Example Code:
Java
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    if (i == 5) continue; // Skip the number 5
    if (i == 8) break;    // Stop the loop entirely at 8
    System.out.print(i + " "); 
}
// Output: 1 2 3 4 6 7
