3. Pass by Value
Java is strictly Pass by Value.
●	When you pass a primitive, a copy of the value is passed.
●	When you pass an object, a copy of the reference (the memory address) is passed.
Wait, what does that mean? It means you can change the contents of an object inside a method, but you cannot change which object the original variable points to.
________________________________________
4. Recursion
Recursion is when a method calls itself to solve a smaller version of the same problem. Every recursive method needs a Base Case to stop the infinite loop.
Java
int factorial(int n) {
    if (n == 1) return 1; // Base Case
    return n * factorial(n - 1); // Recursive Call
}
________________________________________
5. Stack vs. Heap Memory
This is the most critical concept for understanding how Java manages data during execution.
Feature	Stack Memory	Heap Memory
Storage	Primitive values and references to objects.	Actual Objects (like Strings, Arrays, Class instances).
Order	LIFO (Last-In-First-Out).	Random Access.
Lifecycle	Exists only as long as the method is running.	Exists as long as the object is being used.
Size	Smaller, but very fast.	Much larger, but slower.
Example: If you create User user = new User(), the variable user stays on the Stack, but the data (the new User()) is stored on the Heap.
________________________________________
6. Garbage Collection (GC) Basics
In languages like C++, you have to manually delete objects to free memory. In Java, the Garbage Collector does this automatically.
●	How it works: The GC looks for objects on the Heap that are no longer reachable (no variable on the Stack is pointing to them).
●	When it runs: It’s managed by the JVM. You can "suggest" it run using System.gc(), but the JVM decides the actual timing.
________________________________________
Why this matters for Full Stack
When your Angular app makes a request to your Java API, the backend creates objects to handle that request. If you write inefficient code (like creating massive loops of unnecessary objects), you can fill up the Heap, leading to an OutOfMemoryError.
Properly structuring your methods and understanding memory ensures your API stays fast even under heavy load.


1. Stack Memory: The Fast-Paced Organizer
Stack memory is used for execution. It follows the LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) principle. Every time you call a method, a new "block" (stack frame) is created to hold local variables and references to objects.
●	What’s inside: Primitive types (like int, double, boolean) and references (pointers) to objects stored in the heap.
●	Scope: Once a method finishes executing, its stack frame is popped off, and all data within it is instantly gone.
●	Speed: Extremely fast because the memory allocation is simple and managed by the CPU.
________________________________________
2. Heap Memory: The Shared Reservoir
The Heap is where the actual Objects live. When you use the new keyword, Java carves out space in the Heap.
●	What’s inside: All objects (e.g., a String, a HashMap, or your custom User object).
●	Scope: Objects stay here as long as they are being "used" (referenced) by something in the Stack.
●	Speed: Slower than the Stack because it requires complex searching for free space and maintenance by Garbage Collection.
Object Oriented Programming (MOST IMPORTANT 🔥)
1. Classes & Objects
A Class is a template or a blueprint. An Object is a physical reality—an instance of that blueprint.
Think of a "User" in your Angular application. The Class defines that a user has a name and email. The Object is the actual user data coming from your database.
________________________________________
2. Constructors & this Keyword
●	Constructor: A special method used to initialize objects. It has the same name as the class and no return type.
●	this: A reference variable that refers to the current object. It is primarily used to resolve ambiguity between instance variables and parameters.
________________________________________
3. The static Keyword
The static keyword means the member belongs to the class itself rather than a specific object.
●	Static Variables: Shared by all objects of the class (e.g., a counter for total users).
●	Static Methods: Can be called without creating an object (e.g., Math.sqrt()).
________________________________________
4. Initialization Blocks
●	Instance Block: Runs every time an object is created (before the constructor).
●	Static Block: Runs only once when the class is first loaded into memory by the JVM.
________________________________________
5. Comprehensive Example
This example simulates a Product Management System similar to what you might build in a Full Stack project. It combines all the topics above.
Java

class Product {
    // 1. Static Variable (Belongs to Class)
    static String warehouseName;
    static int productCount = 0;

    // 2. Instance Variables (Belongs to Object)
    int productId;
    String productName;
    double price;

    // 3. Static Initialization Block
    static {
        warehouseName = "Central Hub - Bangalore";
        System.out.println("Static Block: Warehouse initialized to: " + warehouseName);
    }

    // 4. Instance Initialization Block
    {
        productCount++; 
        System.out.println("Instance Block: New product being created... Current Total: " + productCount);
    }

    // 5. Parameterized Constructor using 'this'
    public Product(int productId, String productName, double price) {
        this.productId = productId;     // 'this' distinguishes instance var from parameter
        this.productName = productName;
        this.price = price;
        System.out.println("Constructor: Logic for " + this.productName + " completed.");
    }

    // 6. Instance Method
    public void displayDetails() {
        System.out.println("ID: " + productId + " | Name: " + productName + " | Price: $" + price);
    }

    // 7. Static Method
    public static void showWarehouseInfo() {
        System.out.println("All products are stored at: " + warehouseName);
        // System.out.println(productName); // ERROR: Static methods cannot access non-static variables
    }
}

// Main Class to execute the program
public class InventorySystem {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Accessing Static Method without creating an object
        Product.showWarehouseInfo();
        System.out.println("------------------------------------");

        // Creating Objects (Triggers Instance Block and Constructor)
        Product p1 = new Product(101, "Laptop", 850.00);
        p1.displayDetails();

        System.out.println("------------------------------------");

        Product p2 = new Product(102, "Smartphone", 500.00);
        p2.displayDetails();
        
        System.out.println("------------------------------------");
        System.out.println("Final Product Count: " + Product.productCount);
    }
}
