1. Encapsulation (Data Hiding)
Encapsulation is the process of wrapping code and data together into a single unit. We achieve this by making variables private and providing public Getters and Setters.
Why? It prevents unauthorized access and allows you to add validation logic before data is changed.
Java
class Employee {
    // Private data: hidden from outside world
    private int id;
    private String name;
    private double salary;

    // Public Getter and Setter methods
    public void setSalary(double salary) {
        if (salary > 0) { // Validation logic
            this.salary = salary;
        } else {
            System.out.println("Invalid salary amount!");
        }
    }

    public double getSalary() {
        return this.salary;
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public void setName(String name) { this.name = name; }
}

public class EncapsulationDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee emp = new Employee();
        emp.setName("Harsha");
        emp.setSalary(50000); // Setting data through method
        
        System.out.println("Employee: " + emp.getName() + " | Salary: " + emp.getSalary());
    }
}
