3. Polymorphism (Many Forms)
Polymorphism allows us to perform a single action in different ways.
A. Compile-time Polymorphism (Method Overloading)
Resolved during compilation. Multiple methods have the same name but different parameters.
B. Runtime Polymorphism (Method Overriding)
Resolved at runtime. A child class provides a specific implementation of a method already defined in its parent class.
Java
class PaymentGateway {
    // Overloading: Different parameters
    void process(double amount) { 
        System.out.println("Processing generic payment of $" + amount); 
    }
    
    void process(double amount, String coupon) {
        System.out.println("Processing $" + amount + " with coupon: " + coupon);
    }
}

class UPIPayment extends PaymentGateway {
    // Overriding: Changing parent behavior
    @Override
    void process(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing UPI Payment of $" + amount + " via Mobile App.");
    }
}

public class PolyDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PaymentGateway payment = new UPIPayment(); // Upcasting
        
        // This calls the Overridden version in UPIPayment (Runtime Poly)
        payment.process(250.00); 
        
        // This calls the Overloaded version (Compile-time Poly)
        payment.process(200.0, "SAVE10"); 
    }
}
________________________________________
4. Abstraction (Hiding Complexity)
Abstraction is the concept of hiding internal implementation details and showing only the essential features.
●	Abstract Class: Can have both abstract (empty) and concrete (implemented) methods.
●	Interface: A blueprint of a class that only contains abstract methods (until Java 8).
Java
// Abstract Class
abstract class Database {
    abstract void connect(); // No body, implementation hidden
    
    void disconnect() { // Concrete method
        System.out.println("Closing database connection...");
    }
}

class MySqlDB extends Database {
    @Override
    void connect() {
        System.out.println("Connecting to MySQL Database on Port 3306...");
    }
}

class MongoDB extends Database {
    @Override
    void connect() {
        System.out.println("Connecting to MongoDB Atlas...");
    }
}

public class AbstractionDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Database db;
        
        db = new MySqlDB();
        db.connect();
        
        db = new MongoDB();
        db.connect();
        db.disconnect();
    }
}
