3. Polymorphism (Many Forms)
Polymorphism allows us to perform a single action in different ways.
A. Compile-time Polymorphism (Method Overloading)
This occurs when multiple methods have the same name but different parameters (number or type). It is resolved by the compiler.
B. Runtime Polymorphism (Method Overriding)
This occurs when a child class provides a specific implementation for a method already defined in its parent. It is resolved by the JVM at execution time.
Java
class PaymentProcessor {
    // Overloading: Same name, different parameters
    void pay(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing generic payment of: " + amount);
    }

    void pay(double amount, String coupon) {
        System.out.println("Processing " + amount + " with coupon: " + coupon);
    }

    // This method will be overridden
    void processTransaction() {
        System.out.println("General transaction processing...");
    }
}

class CreditCardPayment extends PaymentProcessor {
    @Override
    void processTransaction() {
        System.out.println("Processing Credit Card transaction with encrypted security.");
    }
}

public class PolymorphismMain {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        PaymentProcessor pp = new CreditCardPayment(); // Upcasting
        
        // Overloading call (Compile-time)
        pp.pay(500.0, "SAVE50"); 
        
        // Overriding call (Runtime)
        // JVM calls the child version even though the reference type is parent
        pp.processTransaction(); 
    }
}
