Method Overriding
Method Overriding occurs when a subclass provides a specific implementation for a method that is already defined in its superclass.
●	Rule: The method must have the same name, return type, and parameters.
●	Annotation: We use @Override to tell the compiler to check if we are actually overriding a method (prevents typos).
________________________________________
2. The super Keyword
The super keyword is a reference variable used to refer to immediate parent class objects.
1.	To call parent methods: Useful if the child has overridden them but still needs the original logic.
2.	To call parent constructors: Must be the first statement in the child constructor.
3.	To access parent variables: If the child has a variable with the same name (shadowing).
________________________________________
3. The final Keyword
The final keyword is used to restrict the user in three ways:
●	Final Variable: Creates a constant (value cannot be changed).
●	Final Method: Prevents Method Overriding.
●	Final Class: Prevents Inheritance (the class cannot be extended).
________________________________________
4. The Object Class
In Java, every class implicitly inherits from the java.lang.Object class. It is the root of the entire hierarchy. Common methods you will override in professional projects:
●	toString(): Returns a string representation of the object (great for logging).
●	equals(Object obj): Compares two objects for equality (instead of memory address).
●	hashCode(): Returns a unique integer for the object (used in HashMaps).
________________________________________
5. The instanceof Operator
This is a comparison operator used to check if an object is an instance of a specific class or interface. It returns a boolean.
________________________________________
Comprehensive Example
This example demonstrates a Payment System where we use final to secure business rules and super to reuse logic.
Java
// Root Class (All classes inherit from Object)
class BaseTransaction {
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Base Transaction Record";
    }
}

class Payment extends BaseTransaction {
    double amount;

    Payment(double amount) {
        this.amount = amount;
    }

    // A final method cannot be changed by any child class
    final void showCurrency() {
        System.out.println("Currency: USD");
    }

    void process() {
        System.out.println("Processing payment of $" + amount);
    }
}

class CreditCardPayment extends Payment {
    double serviceFee = 2.50;

    CreditCardPayment(double amount) {
        super(amount); // Calling parent constructor
    }

    @Override
    void process() {
        super.process(); // Executing parent's logic first
        System.out.println("Adding Credit Card fee: $" + serviceFee);
        System.out.println("Total: $" + (amount + serviceFee));
    }

    void validateCard() {
        System.out.println("Card Validated.");
    }
}

public class MainSystem {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Payment p = new CreditCardPayment(100.0);

        // 1. Method Overriding in action
        p.process(); 

        // 2. final usage
        p.showCurrency(); 

        // 3. instanceof operator
        if (p instanceof CreditCardPayment) {
            // Downcasting to access child-specific methods
            CreditCardPayment ccp = (CreditCardPayment) p;
            ccp.validateCard();
        }

        // 4. Object class method
        System.out.println(p.toString());
    }
}
