1. The Immutable Concept & String Pool
In Java, String objects are immutable, meaning once created, their value cannot be changed. If you try to modify a String, Java actually creates a brand-new String object in memory.
The String Constant Pool (SCP)
To save memory, Java uses a special area in the Heap called the String Pool. When you create a string literal, Java checks the pool first. If the string exists, it reuses the reference.
Java
public class StringPoolDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s1 = "Java"; // Created in Pool
        String s2 = "Java"; // Points to the same object as s1
        String s3 = new String("Java"); // Created in Heap (outside pool)

        System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true (Same reference)
        System.out.println(s1 == s3); // false (Different memory locations)
        System.out.println(s1.equals(s3)); // true (Same content)
    }
}
