1. The Concept of Immutability
In Java, the String class is immutable. This means that once a String object is created on the heap, its value cannot be changed.
●	How it works: When you perform an operation like str.concat(" world"), Java doesn't modify the existing string. Instead, it creates a brand-new string object in memory and discards the old reference.
●	Why? Immutability provides Security (usernames/passwords can't be changed mid-flow), Thread Safety (multiple threads can share a string without corruption), and Caching (the String Pool).
________________________________________
2. The String Pool
The String Pool is a special storage area within the Java Heap. It is a cache of String objects.
●	Literal Creation: When you say String s = "Java", Java checks the pool. If "Java" already exists, it returns the existing reference. If not, it creates it.
●	Keyword new: If you say String s = new String("Java"), you force Java to create a new object on the heap, outside the pool, even if "Java" already exists inside the pool.
________________________________________
3. String vs. StringBuffer vs. StringBuilder
If you are doing heavy text manipulation (like a loop appending 1,000 words), using String is expensive because it creates 1,000 objects. This is where Mutable sequences come in.
Feature	String	StringBuffer	StringBuilder
Mutability	Immutable (Fixed)	Mutable (Changeable)	Mutable (Changeable)
Thread Safety	Safe (due to immutability)	Safe (Synchronized)	Not Safe (Not Synchronized)
Performance	Slow for frequent updates	Medium	Fastest
Storage	String Pool / Heap	Heap	Heap
When to use what?
●	String: Use when data won't change often or you're using simple literals.
●	StringBuffer: Use in multi-threaded environments where multiple threads are updating the same string.
●	StringBuilder: Use in single-threaded logic (like most local variables/backend logic) for maximum speed.
________________________________________
4. Implementation Example
Java
public class StringComparison {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // --- IMMUTABILITY & STRING POOL ---
        String s1 = "Hello"; // Goes into String Pool
        String s2 = "Hello"; // References the SAME object in Pool
        String s3 = new String("Hello"); // Creates NEW object in Heap
        
        System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true (Same memory address)
        System.out.println(s1 == s3); // false (Different memory addresses)

        // --- STRINGBUILDER (Mutable) ---
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Java");
        sb.append(" Programming"); // Modifies the SAME object in memory
        System.out.println(sb.toString()); // "Java Programming"

        // --- THE "PASS BY VALUE" TRAP WITH STRINGS ---
        String name = "Gemini";
        changeName(name);
        System.out.println("After method: " + name); // Still "Gemini" because Strings are immutable!
    }

    static void changeName(String n) {
        n = n + " AI"; // This creates a new local object; original remains untouched
    }
}
Summary of Memory Behavior
When you use StringBuilder or StringBuffer, Java uses a resizable array internally. Instead of creating new objects, it simply expands the internal buffer, which is significantly lighter on the Garbage Collector.

1. Functional Interface
🔹 What is a Functional Interface ?
A Functional Interface is an interface that contains exactly one abstract method.
👉 It may contain:
●	multiple default methods
●	multiple static methods
●	methods from Object class
But it must contain only ONE abstract method.
This is important because functional interfaces are the target types for lambda expressions.
