The try and catch Blocks
These two work as a pair. The try block contains the code that might cause an error, and the catch block contains the code that handles the error if it happens.
●	Try: "Try running this code."
●	Catch: "If a specific error occurs, catch it here and do something about it."
Java Example:
Java
public class TryCatchExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int division = 10 / 0; // This will throw an ArithmeticException
            System.out.println("This line will never execute.");
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: You cannot divide by zero!");
            System.out.println("Message: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        System.out.println("The program continues running safely...");
    }
}
________________________________________
2. The throw Keyword
While try-catch is used to handle exceptions, throw is used to explicitly create one. You use this when a specific condition in your logic isn't met (e.g., a user enters a negative age).
Java Example:
Java
public class ThrowExample {
    static void checkAge(int age) {
        if (age < 18) {
            // We manually throw an exception
            throw new ArithmeticException("Access denied - You must be at least 18 years old.");
