The "Chain of Responsibility"
When a method uses throws, it’s essentially saying: "I know an error might happen here, but I don't want to deal with it. Whoever calls me needs to handle it."
Java Code: Multiple Exceptions in throws
In this example, the processData method warns that it might fail for three different reasons. Notice how the main method is then forced to deal with those possibilities.
Java
import java.io.IOException;
import java.sql.SQLException;
import java.rmi.RemoteException;

public class MultiThrowsExample {

    // This method 'throws' three different checked exceptions
    // It doesn't use try-catch; it just passes the risk upward
    public static void processData(int sourceId) 
            throws IOException, SQLException, RemoteException {
        
        if (sourceId == 1) {
            throw new IOException("Failed to read the local file.");
        } else if (sourceId == 2) {
            throw new SQLException("Database connection refused.");
        } else if (sourceId == 3) {
            throw new RemoteException("Cloud server is unreachable.");
        }
        
        System.out.println("Data processed successfully!");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Because processData 'throws' exceptions, main MUST handle them
        try {
            processData(2); 
        } 
        catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("File Error: " + e.getMessage());
        } 
        catch (SQLException e) {
            System.out.println("Database Error: " + e.getMessage());
        } 
        catch (RemoteException e) {
            System.out.println("Network Error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        
        System.out.println("The program finished safely.");
    }
}
