Naming Collisions in Java
Naming collisions occur when two or more identifiers (classes, interfaces, methods, or variables) share the same name in a way that causes ambiguity or conflict in the code.
Types of Naming Collisions:
●	Class vs. Interface Collision: When a class and an interface have the same name in the same package.
●	Interface Method Collision: When a class implements multiple interfaces that declare methods with the same signature.
●	Variable Collision: When interfaces declare variables with the same name, and a class implementing them faces ambiguity.
Example – Method Collision:
interface Animal {
    void makeSound();
}

interface Machine {
    void makeSound();
}

class RobotDog implements Animal, Machine {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("This serves both Animal and Machine!");
    }
}
Here, RobotDog must provide a single implementation of makeSound(), even though both interfaces define it. This can lead to design confusion because the same method is serving two different conceptual purposes.
