Autoboxing and Unboxing in Java
Java introduced autoboxing and unboxing in JDK 5 to make working with primitives and wrapper classes more seamless.
________________________________________
Autoboxing
Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive type into its corresponding wrapper class object.
●	Example: int → Integer, double → Double
●	This happens when a primitive is assigned to a variable of a wrapper type or passed to a method expecting an object.
public class AutoBoxingExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int num = 10;

        // Autoboxing: primitive int → Integer object
        Integer obj = num;

        System.out.println("Integer object: " + obj);
    }
}
________________________________________
Unboxing
Unboxing is the reverse process: automatic conversion of a wrapper class object back into its primitive type.
public class UnboxingExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Integer obj = 25;

        // Unboxing: Integer object → primitive int
        int num = obj;

        System.out.println("Primitive int: " + num);
    }
}
________________________________________
Combined Example
Autoboxing and unboxing often occur together, especially in collections and arithmetic operations.
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class AutoBoxingUnboxingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

        // Autoboxing: int → Integer
        list.add(5);
        list.add(10);

        // Unboxing: Integer → int
        int sum = 0;
        for (Integer i : list) {
            sum += i; // unboxing happens here
        }

        System.out.println("Sum: " + sum);
    }
}
