Functional Interfaces in Java
A functional interface is an interface that contains exactly one abstract method. It can have multiple default or static methods, but only one abstract method. Functional interfaces are the foundation of lambda expressions and method references in Java.
________________________________________
Key Points
●	Introduced in Java 8 to support functional programming.
●	Annotated with @FunctionalInterface (optional but recommended).
●	Can be implemented using lambda expressions, method references, or anonymous classes.
●	Examples in Java’s standard library: 
o	Runnable (method: run())
o	Callable<V> (method: call())
o	Comparator<T> (method: compare(T o1, T o2))
o	Function<T,R> (method: apply(T t))
o	Predicate<T> (method: test(T t))
