1. Filter
How it works: It acts as a gatekeeper. It takes a Predicate (a condition that returns true or false) and only lets the elements that satisfy the condition pass through to the next stage.
Java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie", "David");
List<String> result = names.stream()
    .filter(name -> name.startsWith("C"))
    .collect(Collectors.toList()); 
// Output: [Charlie]
________________________________________
2. Map
How it works: It is used for transformation. It takes a function and applies it to every element in the stream, converting it into something else (e.g., turning a string into its length or an object into one of its fields).
Java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana");
List<Integer> lengths = names.stream()
    .map(String::length)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
// Output: [5, 6]
________________________________________
3. Sorted
How it works: It sorts the elements in the stream. By default, it uses "natural order" (alphabetical or numerical), but you can also provide a custom Comparator to define your own sorting logic.
Java
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(5, 1, 3, 2, 4);
List<Integer> sortedNumbers = numbers.stream()
    .sorted()
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
// Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
________________________________________
4. Collect
How it works: This is a terminal operation. Streams are lazy; they don't do anything until a terminal operation is called. collect gathers the processed elements from the "conveyor belt" and puts them into a new container, like a List, Set, or Map.
Java
List<String> list = Stream.of("a", "b", "c")
    .collect(Collectors.toList());
________________________________________
5. ForEach
How it works: Another terminal operation. Instead of returning a new collection, it performs an action for every element in the stream. It’s typically used for "side effects" like printing data or updating a database.
Java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Alice", "Bob");
names.stream()
    .forEach(name -> System.out.println("Hello " + name));
// Output: 
// Hello Alice
// Hello Bob
________________________________________
6. Reduce
How it works: It combines all elements into a single result. It uses an "accumulator" function. For example, it takes the first two numbers, adds them, takes that result and adds it to the third, and so on until only one value remains.
Java
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4);
int sum = numbers.stream()
    .reduce(0, (a, b) -> a + b);
// Output: 10
