The Anatomy of a Stream
Every Stream operation follows a three-step pattern:
1.	Source: Where the data comes from (e.g., a List or Array).
2.	Intermediate Operations: Transformations that return a new stream (they are "lazy" and don't execute until the end).
3.	Terminal Operation: The final step that produces a result or a side effect (like printing).
________________________________________
2. Practical Examples
Filtering and Collecting
The filter method uses a Predicate to decide which elements stay. The collect method gathers the results back into a container.
Java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class StreamFilterExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie", "Amy", "Dave");

        // Goal: Get names starting with 'A', converted to Uppercase
        List<String> result = names.stream()
            .filter(name -> name.startsWith("A")) // Intermediate
            .map(String::toUpperCase)             // Intermediate (Method Ref!)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());        // Terminal

        System.out.println(result); // [ALICE, AMY]
    }
}
Mapping (Transformation)
map is used to convert an object into something else. Below, we convert a list of Integers into their squares.
