🔹 Example 6: peek() – Debugging Streams
import java.util.*;
import java.util.stream.*;

public class StreamPeek {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Alice", "Bob", "Charlie");

        names.stream()
             .peek(n -> System.out.println("Before map: " + n))
             .map(String::toUpperCase)
             .peek(n -> System.out.println("After map: " + n))
             .forEach(System.out::println);
    }
}
Explanation:
●	peek() is an intermediate operation used for debugging.
●	It allows you to inspect elements as they flow through the pipeline.
●	Not intended for modifying data, just for observation.
________________________________________
🔹 Key Takeaway
Streams let you build pipelines of operations:
●	Source → Collection, array, or generator.
●	Intermediate operations → Transformations (map, filter, flatMap, distinct, etc.).
●	Terminal operations → Produce results (collect, reduce, forEach, match).
